Why America Must Not Reelect President Bush
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and at the same time undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I was damned by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush entered the 2000 election with a platform promising an "humility" foreign policy.
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policies at the ballot box, America has a chance to earn back the world's respect and support.
The terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001, required a strong response.
However, they also led to the undermining of the critical process essential for democracy - the comprehensive and fair discussion of pending problems.
Bush silenced criticism by labeling it as unpatriotic.
For the duration of 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress all dissent.
In this way, he led America in the wrong direction.
Actually, Bush handed Osama bin Laden directly into the hands of his enemies.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and al-Qaeda maintained their training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America were widespread around the world.
This has given way to much greater feelings of resentment.
Today, many more people are willing to risk their lives to kill Americans than on September 11.
Bush likes to claim that the terrorists hate Americans for who they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
Waretheless, war and occupation bring forth innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world counts also the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
No less was the torture of inmates at Abu Ghraib prison the work of just a few "rotten apples".
It was part of a system for dealing with prisoners that was set up by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public opinion condemns America, and our troops in Iraq pay the price for it.
Bush convinced the people that America's security was in good hands under him by addressing the fears that were aroused by the attacks on September 11.
In times of danger, people gather around their flag, and Bush exploited this by promoting a sense of threat.
His campaign assumes that people ultimately do not care about the truth and will almost believe anything if you repeat it often enough.
Something does not seem right with America if we fall for it.
For example, still about 40% of all Americans believe that Saddam Hussein had something to do with 9/11, despite the 9/11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly having established that no such connection existed.
You would want to scream: "Wake up, America.
Don't you see that we're being led by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based on false premises from start to finish - if it ends at all.
It was a war of its own choice, not out of necessity.
Mehr noch, America is under a pretext for going to war: Mass destruction weapons could not be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Then Bush claimed that America went to war to liberate Iraq.
But democracy cannot be imposed on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis—and the world—can be glad that he is gone.
But America had the duty to uphold justice and order; instead, we watched idly as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If we had really been concerned about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a larger number of soldiers for occupation.
We would not only have had to protect the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Even worse: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they employed methods - such as entering private homes and mistreating detainees - that shocked and humiliated the population, fostering resentment and anger.
The backpedaling and blunders of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was disbanded, then America attempted to rebuild it.
First, the USA tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be managed, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protégé with the reputation of a "strongman" - far from a democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to paint a rosy picture, the situation in Iraq is bleak.
A large part of the western sector of the country was left to insurgents. The prospects for the free and fair elections in January are rapidly dimming.
Battlefield for civil war looms.
Bush's war in Iraq has also inflicted colossal damage on America, weakened its military might, and undermined the morale of its troops.
Before the war, America projected an image of overwhelming strength.
No more.
Control over Afghanistan is slipping away.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush Administration on many other political issues, but none of them is as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war have so far amounted to nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush taunted John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would have done differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would have been better positioned to extricate us from our entanglement.
Aber auch ihm wird dies nicht leicht fallen, denn Amerika steckt in einem Sumpf.
Führende Militärexperten und Diplomaten haben Bush händeringend gewarnt, nicht in den Irak einzumarschieren.
Er hat sie ignoriert.
Er hat den kritischen Prozess unterdrückt, mit dem Argument, dass jede Kritik am Oberbefehlshaber die US-Truppen gefährde.
Aber dies ist Bushs Krieg, und er sollte dafür zur Verantwortung gezogen werden.
The Americans should take a moment to ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection might also raise another question: Is Bush's cowboy behavior qualified for him to remain America's commander in chief?
